  <static seed="1330" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/divideRationalExpressions40.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{4y^{2}-49}{2y^{2}+9y+7}} \div ({7-2y}) =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{1}{y+1}, y\ne 3.5\hbox{ and }y\ne -3.5</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{4y^{2}-49}{2y^{2}+9y+7}} \div {7-2y} 
      \amp = {\frac{4y^{2}-49}{2y^{2}+9y+7}} \div \frac{{7-2y}}{1} \\
      \amp = {\frac{4y^{2}-49}{2y^{2}+9y+7}} \cdot {\frac{1}{7-2y}} \\
      \amp =  \frac{{\left(2y+7\right)\mathopen{}\left(2y-7\right)}}{{\left(2y+7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+1\right)}} \cdot \frac{{1}}{{-\left(2y-7\right)}} \\
      \amp = {-\frac{1}{y+1}, y\ne 3.5\hbox{ and }y\ne -3.5}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>2y+7</m> and <m>2y-7</m> were canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification are <m>y \ne {{\frac{7}{2}}\; and \;-{\frac{7}{2}}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
